questionRound.0.question.9.answer: I looked through all of the other people's Payoffs for example  in the above example i looked at who my pay depended on and then who's theirs depended on and so on. In some cases there were obvios choices like Gree was obviously going to choos x becasue those were his two highest numbers. And then i knew other people knew that and they would try to maximinze their score  so i played off of that.  If the coice wasn't obvious i tried to guess what they would choose based on the other  people  and i was right  some of the time.

People are predictable. At first  I was being "nice" by approaching the task in a utilitarian way. After two rounds or so  I then approached it allowing for me to the the highest sum/minimizing risks. It allowed me to do "okay"  but not great. Then  I just "foresaw the future" and based all my decisions of the actions the most relevant person was going to choice because people are predictable  so its easy to win. At the end  I got the best option for me everytime.

The player in the position all the way on the right had the ability to set the standard for each match. The player in the right had the highest quantities by rows instead of conversely diagonal as the other 2/3 players. If you assumed that the right player was going to choose the row with the highest numbers  it would be to everyones best advantage to play off the last players choice. In this case  each person may not have gotten the highest available every time  but it was generally the highest or second highest that each person received. When players merely chose the highest number  it could sometimes prove to be beneficial to them and hurtful to others  or could lead to them getting a low score. By working to the advantage of not just myself but the other players as well [and if other players did this too] we were able to simultaneously maximize each others earnings.

I'm pretty sure my ideas won't be very original  but here goes: After several matches I noticed the color to the right-most part of the screen always had the easiest decision (assuming he/she is of purely rational mind  which I took for granted that everyone was). It was obvious he/she would always lose credits if he/she chose one choice but always guaranteed more if the other choice was taken. Going down the line of the other colors  I could tell which choice each player WILL make (also assuming everyone is of rational mind). In the beginning I had a few frustrating moments where I thought someone was making bad decisions  but in the end my strategy worked  and I'm happy about that.
Identify the player who has an option he or she would definitely choose and logically deduce others' choices.

Basically  I looked at which row would give me the most points and then I looked at the other color's choices that intersected with my choices and determined that the other person would most likely choose the row which would give him/her the most points. Then  I determined the best choice for my color based on what the other person would choose for their own color in order to try and get the most points possible.

The first thing I looked at was if I had an absolute choice. For example  say I am a green player  and if by choosing XG Ir would earn more than choosing YG regardless of what the other color chose  I would start my decision making process from there. If this was not the case  and my maximum profit depended on what the other players chose  I would then check to see if any of the players would make an absolute choice and then back  track from there.
Memorization and Classification of Highest. Also rotating higher and lower playoff selections.

Green's choice is independent of Orange because he will most definitely choose XG as he will always get a bigger payoff by doing so. Thus identify the person whose choice is dependent of the previous player and start deriving from there. Because Green will choose XG  Blue will chose YB to maxmize the profit  and so Red will chose XR  and if I choose XO  i will get 25  which is most likely the biggest profit I would get  even though I could always get 28 if Red miscalculates and chooses YR instead.

I looked for the person who had the clear choice (the option that provided them with two payoffs that were greater than the two payoffs of the other option regardless of the other person's choice). Then I worked my way back. What choice would the person who depended on the person with the clear choice benefit most from? I repeated this procedure until I reached my own choice. If I was the person with the clear choice  then of course I picked that option.

I looked at all of the different options and guessed which color would choose what. If the minimum of one row was equal or higher than the maximum in the other row than I guessed the player would choose the row with the high minimum. I guessed from there who would choose what next.

I first look at what I might want  then see the possible choice of the person who directly affects me; then see his opponet's possible choice  and then see the last person's possible choice. If there is high tendency of any one of them choosing one particular choice  I will just go ahead assume he actually will choose that option  and then think backward to see what possible changes other players will make according to that choice. Finally  I decide whichever will be my best option accordingly.
